== Author, Motivational Speaker and Former Bomb Disposal Operator == 

[[File:Chris Hunter 2011.jpg|thumb|Chris Hunter working in Libya]]


{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2012}}
{{Orphan|date=February 2009}}
{{BLP sources|date=April 2008}}
Major '''Chris Hunter''' [[Queen's Gallantry Medal|QGM]] joined the [[British Army]] in 1989 as a sixteen-year-old army apprentice. He trained initially as a [[Russian language|Russian]] linguist working in defence intelligence and after four years of enlisted service was selected to undergo officer training at the [[Royal Military Academy Sandhurst]]. He graduated at twenty-one, and was subsequently awarded the [[Carmen Sword of Honour]]. He was then commissioned into the [[Royal Logistic Corps]] (RLC)<U+2013>the route that would eventually lead to his becoming an [[Ammunition Technical Officer]] (the British Army<U+2019>s counter-terrorist bomb disposal operators).

[[File:Chris Hunter neutralising RCIED.JPG|thumb|left|Chris Hunter neutralising an RCIED]]


He served as a troop commander on operations in the [[Balkans]], [[East Africa]] and [[Northern Ireland]] and undertook [[arctic warfare]] training in [[Norway]], before becoming an [[Explosive Ordnance Disposal]] (EOD) operator. As an operator he deployed on two high-threat tours in Northern Ireland and one in [[Iraq]], undertook EOD protection duties for the [[Royal Family]] and assisted in the planning and conduct of numerous police arrest operations involving the threat of explosive devices.<ref> http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/terrorism-in-the-uk/8632957/Saved-by-a-bomb-disposal-man.html  </ref> He was also the designated technical Operations Officer for the national contingency response to the terrorist use of a weapon of mass destruction in the UK. He was later involved with a number of UK Special Forces counter terrorism units and saw active service in [[Afghanistan]], [[Colombia]] and Iraq as well as on counter-terrorism operations in the [[UK]].

